Interpolation is the process of estimating an unknown value that falls between known values. In machine learning, this can be done by fitting a model to data and then using the fitted model to estimate the unknown value based on the model inputs. The machine learning approach can sometimes be overkill for simple cases or might not work when we do not have a rich dataset. In these cases, we can turn to conventional interpolation methods such as cubic or linear interpolation. This blog post dives into the application of various conventional interpolation methods.  #machinelearning #datascience

The Vaal dam supplies water to 33% of the population. As of November the 4th, the dam levels were filled at 46.2% of full capacity; as of November the 11th, the dam is only 44.5% filled - a significant reduction to the previous month. September/October of 2019 also saw a 33% drop in capacity compared to last year during the same months. There was also a record low rainfall during the pre-winter season (October to March) where rainfalls are expected to fill the dams; 485.7mm in 2019 compared to 645.8mm in 2018. This lack of rainfall phenomenon coupled with consumption, has put water supply in question.  Lindiwe Sisulu, Minister of Human Settlement, Water and Sanitation, has reassured that no “water-shedding” will occur. Has the government learnt from the Cape Town water crisis in 2017?  EXPLORE Data Science cohort of 2019 looked at some of the factors influential to Cape Town’s water crisis. SQL, Python and PowerBI dashboards were just some industry leading tools used to do the analysis and create beautiful presentations. Five business analytics trends for 2019.  1) Algorithms will become more transparent. Businesses will make it easier to understand what going on behind complex algorithms.   2) There will be a greater adoption of embedded analytics, meaning that users don't have to change from one platform to the next to understand the entirety of the business.   3) Natural language processing will be used to interact with data in a more contextual way.   4) BI platforms will be built to be used. Usage will become more important than it has been in the past where usage is often assumed but not monitored.   5) Greater migration to cloud platforms.  https://www.information-age.com/business-analytics-intelligence-123477004/
